Dear Family and Friends,



I am writing you to share the very sad news that my sister
Sonja took her life on Saturday.



I am going to go ahead and tell you some of the details
because my experience is that many of you will want to know these things,
and I
would rather not have to explain it many times over. Feel free to stop
reading
if you don’t want to know any more.



Sonja has had a very hard time for about a year and a half,
with several long episodes of extreme anxiety and depression. She was under
treatment, having just spent a week in a psychiatric hospital, and was
doing many things right: good diet, lots of exercise, living
in a wonderful cohousing community, being an active neighbor and wonderful
mom,
and lots of positive things to promote mental health. It just didn’t seem
to be enough – she could not shake the overwhelming anxiety, or the
conviction that she was going to be in and out of crisis for the rest of her
life. She felt that her problems were escalating, and that nothing – not
drugs,
not various therapies, not lifestyle – could really turn things around for
her.



This was my third trip out to Portland to visit – the second
in three weeks. Things were up and down in the hospital, but the evening she
was released we had a really enjoyable dinner with friends, and she and I
had a
nice long walk in the arboretum Saturday morning. I felt in some ways that I
had my sister back – we talked widely about all sorts of things – and I was
encouraged that she was able to carry on a conversation with almost no
reference to her situation. I did also have a sense though that part of
her was
elsewhere. When we got home, I wanted to take a nap (I had been sick all
week.)
Pei was also napping. Sonja left. I got worried when she didn’t return and
called the police to tell them I was concerned about suicide. They called me
back to tell me that she had jumped from the building she worked in downtown.



Pei is doing as well as anyone could possibly be expected to
do, as she has been during the whole period of Sonja’s difficulties. She is
very loved and appreciated in Cascadia Commons, the cohousing community that
she and Sonja live in, and is spending quality time with a lot of good,
long-term friends of various ages. I expect to stay here until she graduates
from high school this spring – this will allow her to live at home and
keep as
many things the same as possible. I am working on arranging a leave from
my job
for the remainder of the semester.



The community is being absolutely wonderful – they are
helping in so many ways already, and I can’t imagine a better place to be
to go
through this very difficult period. Last night they all wanted to gather to
support each other and Pei and me, have a potluck and process what had
happened. They’re good people, and we’ll get through this. Sonja was a
beloved member of the community – one of the old timers – and invested so
much
here. Pei and I will reap the benefits of that in the coming months.



We are thinking ahead a bit to a memorial, but probably
won’t commit to a specific date right away. We’ll see how things are
going. It
certainly won’t be this month, but I think sometime in March is likely. We’ll
let you know more as plans develop.



For the coming week, while I would love to talk with some of
you I think I’m going to feel really scattered and crazy if I get a lot of
calls. Pei feels the same. I think she needs space and privacy as much as
anything, and doesn’t mostly want to talk to people.  She knows she is
loved and that people want to
help in any way they can, and she may reach out on her own steam. I would be
fine with getting emails – and I may not get to them right away or respond.
That doesn’t mean I won’t appreciate hearing from you! I’m betting that when
the dust settles in a couple of weeks, I’ll have a bit more leisure to
check in
with people and talk, and I will be glad to be in touch.



I’m doing okay – my pattern will probably be to
over-function for a while and then crash for a while. I am already delegating
like crazy to kind and generous Cascadians, and taking on the jobs that feel
most meaningful to me like writing to you.



My address into June will be:

4373 SW 94th Ave.

Portland OR 97225

The home landline is 503-644-1535

My cell, which I am newly kicked into using, is
920-509-9607.

email: katgriffith@hotmail.com
Much love to you all.Kat


